<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-886-980  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 886 980.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 13 1989 v6 n45 p98(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>S/370 comm upgrades to improve SNA efficiency. (IBM ACF/VTAM,ACF/NCP)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musich, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product enhancement).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   ACF/VTAM 3.0 (Computer network software) (product enhancement)ACF/NCP (Computer network software) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     EnhancementsSNACommunications Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Paula MusichandM;IBM recently announced new releases of  its System/370 mainframecommunications software and front-end processor software designed to improvethe performance and flexibility of SNA networks.andM;Enhancements to IBM's Advanced Communications Function/VirtualTelecommunications Access Method (ACF/VTAM) software and to its AdvancedCommunications Function/Network Control Program (ACF/NCP) support additionaltransmission capacities between Systems Network Architecture (SNA)mainframes, as well as between mainframes and 3745 or 3720 front-endprocessors, IBM officials said.andM;The packages now include a feature called parallel transmission groups,previously supported only on slower-speed Synchronous Data Link Control linesbetween front-end processors and 3270 devices.andM;Parallel transmission groups increase available bandwidth and eliminate asingle point of failure by providing parallel channel connections to a VTAMhost, said David Passmore, a partner in the Network Strategies ConsultingPractice of Ernst andamp; Young, a communications consulting firm based in Fairfax,Va.andP;  &quot;You can have two paths between the same pair of VTAM hosts, and you canhave parallel channel connections between the VTAM host and its front end,&quot;said Passmore, who has been briefed on the new releases.andM;IBM also increased the software's flexibility for networking SNA hosts andfront-end processors with the addition of a new feature called the casualconnection.andM;This feature, which requires the use of Node Type 2.1 peer-to-peer protocols,allows different NCP nodes in the same or separate SNA networks to moreeasily establish links with each other, said Micks  Purnell, a productadministrator in IBM's marketing and service group in White Plains, N.Y.andM;ACF/VTAM Version 3 Release 3 and ACF/NCP Version 5 Release 3 will supportSystem/370 mainframes running the MVS/ESA, MVS/XA and VM/SP operatingsystems.andP;  The MVS versions of the new VTAM will be available in December,followed by the VM versions in June 1990.andP;  The new NCP for MVS will beavailable in December; the VM version will be available in January.andP;  Pricingvaries widely depending on operating environment and front-end processor;upgrades will be free for existing customers.andO;</TEXT></DOC>